<h2>Improving the formula</h2>
<p>The next question came six months later:</p>
<pre><a href=3D"https://www.nctm.org/archives/library/drmath/view/55252.htm=
l">Volume of a Trapezoidal Solid</a>

I have a volume that is <strong>75 ft long</strong>. The front of the figur=
e is <strong>57 ft wide, 35 ft high</strong>, while the rear is <strong>72 =
ft wide, 12 ft high</strong>. I know how to figure the volume L*W*H and the=
 area L*W, but how do I account for the slope of the ceiling and the opposi=
te widths?</pre>
<p>Here I=E2=80=99ve drawn it flipped onto the front, putting it in our usu=
al orientation for a frustum:</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" class=3D"aligncenter size-full wp-image-12421" src=
=3D"https://www.themathdoctors.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/ADM55252-non-=
frustum.png" alt=3D"" width=3D"272" height=3D"492"></p>
<p>Having done some more thinking this time, I answered again:</p>
<pre>Hi, Greg.

It sounds like your shape can be thought of as a 57x35 foot rectangle at th=
e front, joined by planes to a 72x12 foot rectangle at the back, 75 feet aw=
ay. Here is a formula for the volume of that shape, which I will draw as a =
frustum-like figure with rectangular top and bottom rather than front and b=
ack (since that is the form in which I have most often dealt with it):

                       a2
               +---------------+
            b2/               / \---------
             +---------------+   \      |
            /                |    \     |
           /.................|.... +    | h
          /                  |    /     |
         /                   |   /      |
        /                    |  /b1 ------
       /                     | /
      /                      |/
     +-----------------------+
                a1

     V =3D [a1*b1 + a2*b2 + (a1*b2 + a2*b1)/2] * h/3

Here the bottom is a1 x b1, and the top is a2 x b2, with the a's parallel a=
nd the b's parallel (this is important).</pre>
<p>This is the formula we saw before.</p>
<pre>An <strong>alternative version of the formula</strong>, using the aver=
age length and width, is:

     V =3D [a1*b1 + a2*b2 + 4((a1+a2)/2 * (b1+b2)/2)] * h/6
          \___/   \___/     \___________________/
        area of  area of          area of
         bottom    top             middle
       rectangle rectangle       rectangle

The "middle" rectangle has sides that are the average of the sides of the t=
op and bottom rectangles:

                       a2
               +---------------+
            b2/               / \---------
             +---------------+   +      |
            /                |  / \     |
           /.................|./.. +    | h
          /                  |/   /     |
         +-------------------+   /      |
        /      (a1+a2)/2     |  /b1 ------
       /                     | /
      /                      |/
     +-----------------------+
                a1</pre>
