<h2>The general concept: prismatoids</h2>
<p>A 2002 question finally asked about the calculus derivation of the origi=
nal formula:</p>
<pre><a href=3D"https://www.nctm.org/archives/library/drmath/view/51841.htm=
l">Frustum of a Pyramid with a Rectangular Base</a>

Back in 2000 you gave a solution you derived using calculus to someone want=
ing to know how to figure the volume of a rectangular based frustum of a py=
ramid see:=20

   Volume of a Frustum-Like Structure
   <a href=3D"https://www.nctm.org/archives/library/drmath/view/55226.html"=
>http://mathforum.org/dr.math/problems/cunningham.5.12.00.html</a>  =20

   V =3D a1b1 + a2b2 + (a1b2 + a2b1)/2 x h/3

I am an engineer with a water treatment agency and need to figure the amoun=
t of <strong>water per foot of elevation</strong> in our reservoirs that ha=
ppen to have the same shape as previously described. To satisfy my curiosit=
y, could you please send me a copy of your derivation? I have had up throug=
h differential equations in college and am a bit rusty, so lay it on me.</p=
re>
<p>I answered with a reference to the last answer, some new discoveries I=
=E2=80=99d made, and a hint to the derivation:</p>
<pre>Hi, Brad.

You'll be interested in this later page, where I answered a question like y=
ours about the volume contained by such a shape up to a given depth:

   Volume of a Trapezoidal Solid
   <a href=3D"https://www.nctm.org/archives/library/drmath/view/55252.html"=
>http://mathforum.org/dr.math/problems/greg.11.15.00.html</a>  =20

It will also be of interest to you that the shape under discussion is a spe=
cial case of a more general shape I wasn't aware of at the time, called the=
 <strong>prismoid</strong>, or, even more generally, a <strong>prismatoid</=
strong>:

   MathWorld - Eric Weisstein:

   <a href=3D"http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Prismoid.html">http://mathworld.=
wolfram.com/Prismoid.html</a>  =20
   <a href=3D"http://mathworld.wolfram.com/Prismatoid.html">http://mathworl=
d.wolfram.com/Prismatoid.html</a>  =20

The latter page gives the same formula as in my reference above, for the vo=
lume in this much more general case, where you just have <strong>two parall=
el polygonal bases</strong> joined to one another by <strong>straight edges=
</strong>:

    V =3D h/6 (A1 + 4M + A2)

where h is the altitude, A1 and A2 are the areas of the bases, and M is the=
 area of the cross section halfway between.</pre>
<p>A prismatoid might, for example, have an irregular quadrilateral base an=
d a triangular top, joined by straight line segments like this:</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" class=3D"aligncenter wp-image-12425 size-medium" s=
rc=3D"https://www.themathdoctors.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/ADM51841-pr=
ismatoid-300x294.png" alt=3D"" width=3D"300" height=3D"294"></p>
<p>The polygon <em>M</em> will differ according to how vertices in the top =
and bottom are joined, so it plays an important role in the formula:</p>
<p><img loading=3D"lazy" class=3D"aligncenter wp-image-12426 size-medium" s=
rc=3D"https://www.themathdoctors.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/ADM51841-pr=
ismatoid-1-300x290.png" alt=3D"" width=3D"300" height=3D"290"></p>
<p>The fact that my formula (in this form) extends beyond the case I=E2=80=
=99d proved it for is not too surprising, but the extreme generality is ama=
zing. And the formula can extend even further, to the <a href=3D"https://ma=
thworld.wolfram.com/GeneralPrismatoid.html">general prismatoid</a>.</p>
<h3>Deriving our formula: calculus</h3>
<p>Now we consider his actual question, deriving my original formula:</p>
<pre>Now, my <strong>calculus derivation</strong> for our special case was =
based on the fact that the length and width are changing linearly with heig=
ht. So the dimensions of the rectangular cross-section at height x will be

    a =3D a1 + (a2-a1) * x/h
    b =3D b1 + (b2-b1) * x/h

(To check these, see what they are at x=3D0 and x=3Dh.)

Then I integrated the product ab with respect to x, from 0 to h. It's a pre=
tty easy integration.

I later rederived the same formula by <strong>dissecting</strong> the shape=
 into several prisms and pyramids. That takes a little more visualization a=
nd calculation, but no calculus.</pre>
<p>We=E2=80=99ll carry this out below.</p>
<p>Brad succeeded with the hint, but needed another:</p>
<pre>Thank you for the information. I was able to integrate it and come up =
with the same answer. My only other question is what principle or theorem y=
ou used for the <strong>a and b of the rectangular cross-section</strong> a=
t any height x?

   a =3D a1 + (a2-a1) * x/h
   b =3D b1 + (b2-b1) * x/h

Once again, thanks for your prompt response to my inquiry.</pre>
<p>This was the easy part (sort of). I answered:</p>
<pre>Hi, Brad.

You can just draw a side view:

                a1
          +------------+ -------------
         /            . \       |x  |
        /            .   \      |   |
       +------------+-----+ ------  |h
      /            .       \        |
     /     a1     .  a2-a1  \       |
    +------------+-----------+ -------
                a2

You can see that the width at distance x from the top is a1 + (a2-a1)x/h, u=
sing similar triangles. (I've got this upside-down from the original labeli=
ng, but that doesn't affect the math.)

Is that what you wanted?</pre>
<p>Brad replied:</p>
<pre>Aha, I see the light. I guessed you were probably using similar triang=
les but was having a hard time visualizing it for some reason. Thank you fo=
r your time and patience with a math-rusty engineer. You have been most hel=
pful.</pre>
<p>Now let=E2=80=99s do it. It turns out to look a lot like my dissection p=
roof!</p>
